<DOC><DOCNO> AP890913-0264 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-13-89 0801EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-AMR-Airbus     09-13 0233</FIRST><SECOND>PM-AMR-Airbus,0243</SECOND><HEAD>Report: Airline Expected to Place Plane Orders</HEAD><DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   American Airlines Inc. this fall willplace orders and options for 12 European-built Airbus airliners in atransaction valued at nearly $850 million, a newspaper reportedtoday.   Industry sources familiar with the negotiations told The DallasMorning News that the Fort Worth-based airline plans to place firmorders for six Airbus A300-600R aircraft and get options for anothersix.   The sources told the newspaper an announcement for the ordercould come within the next two months.   However, officials at AMR Corp., the parent of American, andAirbus Industries, based in Toulouse, France, would not comment onwhether a deal is near.   American's vice president and treasurer, Michael Durham,confirmed the airline has been looking at several aircraft,including the Airbus, in search of a plane that could be used onoverwater routes to destinations in Europe and the Caribbean.   Fulfilling that priority is the carrier's top priority in therealm of aircraft acquisition, said Durham.   The airline was the launch customer for the A300-600R and hastaken delivery of 25 copies of the model, officials said. Theairline uses the planes on its route system in the Caribbean, whereit has a hub at San Juan, Puerto Rico.   The A300-600R is a newer, longer-range version of Airbus' A300and has a price tag of $71 million, officials said.</TEXT></DOC>